cl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><span class=\"fn\">x</span> <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Eq\">=</a> <span class=\"fn\">y</span></div></div>","info":{"doc":"","docLink":"./Std/Time/DateTime/WallTime.html#Std.Time.WallTime.ext","kind":"theorem","line":29,"name":"Std.Time.WallTime.ext","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/62eed1db4d67327ec8120be05f1a1b0847d74561/src/Std/Time/DateTime/WallTime.lean#L29-L29"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">structure</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Std/Time/DateTime/WallTime.html#Std.Time.WallTime\"><span class=\"name\">Std</span>.<span class=\"name\">Time</span>.<span class=\"name\">WallTime</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./foundational_types.html\">Type</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"A wall-clock time is what a clock shows in a given timezone: the local civil time at some point in\ntime. It is stored as a `Duration` since `1970-01-01T00:00:00` in local time, equivalent to a\n`PlainDateTime` packed into a single offset, which makes arithmetic straightforward.\n\nEvery timezone induces a correspondence between `Timestamp` and `WallTime`: interpreting a\n`Timestamp` in a timezone yields the `WallTime` (what a clock in that timezone reads at that\ninstant), and resolving a `WallTime` in a timezone yields the `Timestamp` (the absolute instant the\nclock reading refers to).\n","docLink":"./Std/Time/DateTime/WallTime.html#Std.Time.WallTime","kind":"structure","line":19,"name":"Std.Time.WallTime","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/62eed1db4d67327ec8120be05f1a1b0847d74561/src/Std/Time/DateTime/WallTime.lean#L19-L37"}}],"imports":["Init.System.IO","Std.Time.Duration"],"instances":[{"className":"Repr","name":"Std.Time.instReprWallTime","typeNames":["Std.Time.WallTime"]},{"className":"Decidable","name":"Std.Time.instDecidableEqWallTime","typeNames":["Eq"]},{"className":"In